   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">a program which has among its planks the following :</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">&quot; Predominance of the farmer and other producers on the</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">Federal Reserve Board , that they may control the country&apos; s</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">credit, which is rightfully theirs.&quot;</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">This possibility is no longer pure apprehension . We now</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">have the record of the will of the majority of our most con servative party in a state dominated by a fair average Ameri</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">can voter .</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">The effect of the intervention of political discretion is dis</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">cussed by a much more competent authority :</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">&quot; Nevertheless, Congress has now passed the bill to modify the complexion of the Board, for the very purpose of</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">minimizing expert judgment and giving greater strength to the popular influence most likely to lead it into error. . . . The objection to the measure is not that it is dan gerous to have a farmer on the Board , but that all the argu ments for it have been unsound . It has been carried through by one of the spasms of ill-informed opinion of which the</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2">creation of the &apos;bloc&apos; itself is the chief expression .&quot; ?</text:p>
